<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,282,705]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Remarks. The 
<collectionCode box="[368,413,390,417]" country="Germany" name="Museum Donaueschingen" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">MD</collectionCode>
<specimenCount box="[414,568,390,417]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="generic">50 specimens</specimenCount>
are 6.5–7.0 mm dd, disc pentagonal or slightly indented interradially, with margin covered in small rugose granules and centre with small cylindrical spines with terminal thorns, radial shields raised and rib like with oval distal section exposed (
<figureCitation box="[753,845,462,489]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
), oral shields trapezoid to hemispherical, two times as wide as long, three to four conical to capitate rugose oral papillae (
<figureCitation box="[982,1073,498,525]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
), DAPs fan to kite-shaped and separate, to eight arm spines with tiny thorns, upper to three segments long and one tiny spiniform thorny tentacle scale. They are morphologically consistent with material from the North Atlantic including the 
<typeStatus box="[1247,1295,571,597]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">type</typeStatus>
description. Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Paterson, G. L. J." box="[263,440,606,633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref35334" refString="Paterson, G. L. J. (1985) The deep-sea Ophiuroidea of the North Atlantic Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Zoology, 49, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1985">Paterson (1985)</bibRefCitation>
considered this species to be a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="Verrill, 1885" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1885" box="[939,1316,606,633]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="enopla">
<emphasis box="[939,1167,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Ophiacantha enopla</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." box="[1173,1316,606,633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref36586" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1885) Notice of the remarkable marine fauna occupying the outer banks off the southern coast of New England, No. 11. American Journal of Science, 29, 149 - 157. https: // doi. org / 10.2475 / ajs. s 3 - 29.170.149" type="journal article" year="1885">Verrill, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov &amp; Litvinova (2008)</bibRefCitation>
re-established 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koehler" authorityYear="1907" box="[540,658,643,669]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="veterna">
<emphasis box="[540,658,643,669]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">O. veterna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a full species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Paterson, G. L. J." box="[856,1053,642,669]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref35334" refString="Paterson, G. L. J. (1985) The deep-sea Ophiuroidea of the North Atlantic Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Zoology, 49, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1985">Paterson’s (1985)</bibRefCitation>
record of this species from 
<quantity box="[1365,1437,642,669]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.01" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="101.0">101 m</quantity>
is a depth outlier that requires re-examination. All other records are from 
<quantity box="[973,1131,678,705]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="1850.0" valueMax="2700.0" valueMin="1000.0">1000–2700 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
